Programme sind interaktiv und ermöglichen Diskussionen zu sozialen, politischen, aber auch persönlichen Problemen.  aNew media laws and technologies are currently changing radio in West Africa. Tilo Grätz analyzes this change using the example of the appropriation of radio technologies in Benin. He shows that the processes take place in the interplay of producers, listeners, and technical capabilities under the influence of institutions of media politics. Local radio cultures develop which manifest themselves in typical subjects, program formats, and everyday radio use practices. The most successful programs are interactive and facilitate discussion on social and political as well as personal problems. Technological dramas (Pfaffenberger) accompany the varied development of Beninese radio cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRadio broadcastingxSocial aspectszBenin. 0aRadio broadcastingzBenin. 0aTechnological innovationszBenin. 4aAfrika. 4aAnaloge Medien. 4aBenin. 4aEthnologie. 4aMedien. 4aMedienwandel. 4aMedienwissenschaft. 4aTechnologie. 4aWestafrika. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAnalogue Media.  aEthnology.  aMedia Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Complete eBook Package 2014-2016z9783110489842oZDB-23-TGP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript: Complete eBook-Package 2014z9783110401226oZDB-23-TGP40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839425916zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839425916423Coveruhttps: